%BOM---------------------
Date:12/24/2006 8:00:49 PM
From:Spekulatius
regarding CHK - i do not know all that much about the E&P industry as well but
i do know how to read a cash flow statement. With respect to CHK it is clear
that they are spending more than they take in, supposedly to increase their
reserves. This is fine in my opinion but it turns out that the aggressive
acquisitions tend to dilute shareholder value, since reserves/share are lower
now than thy have been 12/31/05. Feel free to check my numbers they are from
CHK's last presentation and their 10k. CHK tends to increase their sharecount
by 20% annually but their reserves have been growing less than that. the
increase in DDA expenses of 20%+ this year is quite remarkable considering the
fact that this is a company with a long reserve life which should dampen the
impact of cost increases. Since they continue to book new reserves at cost this
does not hit the income statement directly (note that the book value for their
reserves/share has increased even though each share represents less reserves in
mcfe compared to 12/31/05.

I do not know why some officers have been buying CHK shares aggressively in
spring/summer 2006 but I do know that some of their buys are underwater.I do
not want to imply that CHK is a dishonest organization but i have learned to
interpret cash flow statement ever since I lost some money in Worldcom stock -
CHK simply does not pass the smell test.
%EOM----------------------

